Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This project involves the data analysis for movies shows. The dataset source is from "The Movie Database (TMDB)". The dataset comprises of about 10866 rows and 21 columns. The key features include the director of each movie, keywords, runtime, genres, production companies, release year, taglin, overview, vote count, vote average, release year, budget and revenue. We will be interested in finding an insight on the kind of movie that attract viewer which makes them to give high rating. We will also also check for the kinds of attributes viewer check in the movie which return high revenue to the movie industry.

Questions for our Analysis¶

In our investigation, we will answer the following questions:

  • What kind of movie genres yield the highest profit?
  • What characteristics are linked to the popularity of the movies?
  • Which director is the most well-known and makes the most money from his films?

To begin with, we will import libraries for loading our dataset and visualization tools.

In [7]:
# percentage of missing value function

def missing_percent(column_name):
    '''function to check the percent of missing values in the columns
        store the column name and get the count of the missing values 
        in the column and divide by total number of rows
    '''
    
    column_name = sum(df[column_name].isnull())/len(df)*100
    return  round(column_name, 2)

Data Cleaning¶

During the data wrangling process, we discovered some intriguing facts about our data. We will ensure the quality of our data in this part by taking the following steps:

  • remove cast columns from the dataframe
  • in the genre and director columns, separate the pipe icon
  • change the release_date from string to a date time data type
  • Remove the homepage column from the dataframe
  • Drop the tagline column and replace missing values in the overview, director, and genres columns with mode of the data
  • Remove the rows in the revenue and budget columns that contain zeros;
  • add a new column named "profit" to calculate the profit earned for each movie.

First, we'll make a copy of our dataset in case we need to go back to a certain column later on in the analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

To address our research questions, we will analyze our data by computing statistics and creating visualizations. We'll use several plot types to uncover insights and identify trends.

Tip: - Investigate the stated question(s) from multiple angles. It is recommended that you be systematic with your approach. Look at one variable at a time, and then follow it up by looking at relationships between variables. You should explore at least three variables in relation to the primary question. This can be an exploratory relationship between three variables of interest, or looking at how two independent variables relate to a single dependent variable of interest. Lastly, you should perform both single-variable (1d) and multiple-variable (2d) explorations.

Question 1: What kind of movie genres yield the highest profit?¶

In [43]:
# Separate the elements in the genre columns containing multiple values
df_m['genres']=df_m['genres'].str.split("|",expand=True)
 
# Get the count of different genres movies and display the visual
df_m['genres'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar');

From this visual above, we can see that Drama, Comedy, Action, Horror and Adventure movies are the top 5 genre. Now, let's explore more to get insight on which among these yields the highest profit.

def graph_styling(xlabel = '', ylabel = '', title = ''):
    '''function for styling visualization'''
    
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show();

Conclusions¶

We can conclude that movies about adventures and science fiction made the most profit. We have saw that the movie industry grows in popularity year after year as the budget grows. We also discovered that Collin Trevorrow is the most popular director based on our data.

Limitations¶

There are much too many zeros in both the budget and revenue columns. To replace these figures, we applied mean. This may not be the best solution. As a result, more research into how to deal with zero-valued properties is required.
